<!-- .SH "NAME" -->
<A name=>

     <H3>NAME</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
tomoyo-notifyd - policy violation notification daemon for TOMOYO Linux
<!-- .SH "SYNOPSIS" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=1>

     <H3>SYNOPSIS</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .B tomoyo-notifyd -->
<B>tomoyo-notifyd</B> <!-- .SH "DESCRIPTION" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>DESCRIPTION</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
This program detects policy violations that occur in domains set to enforcing mode and notifies the system administrator. The notification method can for example be by sending a mail, but any command can be specified in the configuration file, which is found at <I>/etc/tomoyo/tools/notifyd.conf</I>. This makes it possible to be notified about policy violations as soon as possible, and allows subsequent action to be taken within a short period of time.
<!-- .SH "EXAMPLES" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>EXAMPLES</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<!-- .B Wait for 180 seconds before rejecting the request and send a notification mail: -->
<B>Wait for 180 seconds before rejecting the request and send a notification mail:</B> <!-- .nf -->
<PRE>
tomoyo-notifyd 180 &#146;mail <A HREF="mailto:admin@example.com">admin@example.com</A>&#146;
<!-- .fi -->
</PRE>
<!-- .PP -->
<P>
<!-- .B Reject the request immediately and send a notification using curl: -->
<B>Reject the request immediately and send a notification using curl:</B> <!-- .nf -->
<PRE>
tomoyo-notifyd 0 &#146;curl --data-binary @- <A HREF="https://your.server/path_to_cgi">https://your.server/path_to_cgi</A>&#146;
<!-- .fi -->
</PRE>
<!-- .SH "NOTES" -->
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A name=>

     <H3>NOTES</H3>

</A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
This program should be started from the appropriate stage during startup, for example in <I>/etc/rc.local</I>.
<!-- .PP -->
<P>
Before this program can be invoked, it must be registered in <I>/sys/kernel/security/tomoyo/manager</I>. After initializing policy, this is usually as simple as rebooting the system.
